{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"434aa528-e668-49ef-8e1b-95e434abe0d5","content":"In modern MSTest (3.8+), you can inject `TestContext` via the constructor and use `IAsyncInitialization` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor (TestContext injected automatically)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (runs after constructor, before tests)\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        var result = await _service.DoWorkAsync();\n        Assert.IsNotNull(result);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection**: MSTest 3.x+ automatically passes `TestContext` to the constructor — no `[TestInitialize]` or property setter needed.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`**: Implement this interface (single method `Task InitializeAsync()`) for async setup that must complete before any test runs.\n- **Execution order**: Constructor → `InitializeAsync()` → each `[TestMethod]`.\n- You can still use `[TestCleanup]` or implement `IAsyncDisposable`/`IDisposable` for teardown.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ce8dd45-4433-4852-b724-b4683b976915","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"BD02:158C5C:1E796F1:2262E7E:6A07CCA7"},"id":"d887d293-9c3c-45c6-a404-ac7e07974c06","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:47:28.225Z","parentId":"ad746d49-a8a0-41a1-bf41-459ed898d8a3"}
